{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"fields":{"description":"Harden `infra/scripts/autodeploy.sh` against disk exhaustion from repeated failed rebuilds (incident 2731: 41h of per-main-advance rebuild attempts accumulated multi-GB buildkit cache + dangling layers on the 30G root disk until pip/clone ENOSPC fail-closed the LLM-Review gate). Today `docker image prune -f` runs ONLY on the success path (line 166) and nothing ever prunes the buildkit build cache on either path — a failing deploy loop is exactly when garbage accumulates fastest and is exactly the path with no reclamation.\n\n## What (pinned design — no alternatives left to the executor)\n- Add one helper `prune_docker_caches()` in autodeploy.sh that runs, best-effort:\n  1. `docker builder prune -f --keep-storage \"${BUILD_CACHE_KEEP:-5GB}\"` — a HARD storage cap on the buildkit cache (quantified bound; `--filter until=…` was rejected as time-based and unbounded under a tight failure loop). `BUILD_CACHE_KEEP` joins the existing tunables block (overridable via /etc/rebar/autodeploy.env).\n  2. `docker image prune -f` — dangling images from failed/superseded builds.\n  Both invocations append `>/dev/null 2>&1 || true`: a prune failure must NEVER mask the deploy-failure exit code or alter control flow (same idiom as the existing success-path prune).\n- Call `prune_docker_caches` from `record_backoff_failure()` — the single seam every failure exit already goes through (build fail, health-check rollback, checkout/rsync fail) — so every failed attempt reclaims before backing off.\n- Replace the success path's bare `docker image prune -f` with the same helper, so the buildkit cache is also capped on success (the incident's cache accumulated across BOTH outcomes; keeping ≤5GB warm cache preserves rebuild speed).\n- Note: on the health-check-rollback path the freshly built image is TAGGED (`:latest` re-tagged from `:prev` after rollback leaves the bad build's layers referenced by nothing after the next successful build); the `--keep-storage` builder cap plus dangling-image prune is the bounded, safe reclamation — we deliberately do NOT delete tagged images (`:prev` is the rollback lifeline).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] AC1 (failure path prunes): with `docker` stubbed by a PATH-front shim that logs argv and exits per-scenario, driving `record_backoff_failure` records exactly one `builder prune -f --keep-storage 5GB` and one `image prune -f` invocation, and the function still writes the backoff file with the original fail count — proving command recorded in verify_commands (stub-based, no docker daemon needed).\n- [ ] AC2 (prune failure is inert): with the stub forcing both prune commands to exit 1, `record_backoff_failure` still records the backoff and the script exits with the original failure code — the prune can never mask the deploy failure.\n- [ ] AC3 (bounded growth, quantified): the buildkit cache bound is the `--keep-storage` value (default 5GB, tunable via `BUILD_CACHE_KEEP`); asserted by grep that no `docker builder prune` invocation exists without `--keep-storage`.\n- [ ] AC4 (syntax + config-check): `bash -n infra/scripts/autodeploy.sh` passes and `make config-check` stays green (check 4 covers script syntax)."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783685926323455001,"uuid":"5e402950-86f5-4fc6-81b7-5b6afcb60526"}